      Product Description

      UGREEN Aluminum USB C Hard Drive Enclosure for 2.5" SATA SSD HDD UGREEN Aluminum USB C Hard Drive Enclosure for 2.5" SATA SSD HDD UGREEN USB C Hard Drive Enclosure for 2.5" SATA SSD HDD UGREEN USB Hard Drive Enclosure for 2.5" SATA SSD HDD UGREEN USB Hard Drive Enclosure for 2.5" SATA SSD HDD UGREEN Hard Drive Enclosure for 2.5/3.5" SATA SSD HDD
      Compatibility 2.5" SSD&HDD 2.5" SSD&HDD 2.5" SSD&HDD 2.5" SSD&HDD 2.5" SSD&HDD 2.5/3.5" SSD&HDD
      USB Interface USB C 3.1 Gen 2 USB C 3.1 Gen 2 USB C 3.1 Gen 2 Micro USB 3.0 Micro USB 3.0 USB B 3.0
      Included Cable USB-C to USB-C USB-A to USB-C USB-A to USB-C USB-A to Micro USB 3.0 USB-A to Micro USB 3.0 USB-A to USB-B 3.0
      Cable Length 50cm 50cm 50cm 30cm 50cm 1m
      Transfer Speed 6Gbps 6Gbps 6Gbps 5Gbps 5Gbps 5Gbps
      UASP ✓ ✓ ✓ ✓ ✓ ✓
      Max Capacity Supported 6TB 6TB 6TB 6TB 6TB 16TB

      Great Portability for Your 2.5" Hard Drive

      • Ideal for harnessing your old 2.5"HDD and SSD hard drive as an external USB drive, the USB-C hard drive enclosure will provide you greater convenience of use and versatility of digital data storage. An ideal choice for digital lovers, movie lovers and business elites.

      Latest USB C 3.1 Gen 2 Port, Ensure Fast Transfer and Easy Plug

      • With reversible USB-C, it is convenient to plug and unplug. The USB C port adopts USB 3.1 Gen 2 standard, assuring you the highest speed of data transfer.

      Accelerated UASP, Faster and More Efficient

      • Enhanced with the UASP protocol, delivering up to 70% faster performance than conventional USB 3.0. The 6Gbps max speed makes you transfer 1GB file just in only 3 seconds.

      Easy Usage, Full Protection

      • Plug and play, no driver needed.
      • Easy assembly in seconds, tool- free.
      • Equipped soft EVA foams inside, protecting your hard disks from improper shaking and scratches.
      • Elegant brushed housing with fireproof, shockproof ABS material, makes the case a beautiful addition to your desk.
      • 3 Minutes Auto Sleep Mode, it will go into sleeping mode automatically, which greatly save power and decrease wear and tear of your hard drive.

      Read more

      Enclosure Specification

      • 1. Supports Windows 2000 / XP / Vista / 7/8 / 8.1 / 10, LINUX, Mac OS 8.0 etc.
      • 2. Size: L28.5*W82*H14(mm)
      • 3. Cable Length: 50cm

      Note: This enclosure only comes with a USB-C to USB-A 3.0 cable.

      For Using with Mac, pls make sure to use a USB-C to USB-C cable(Not Included).

      Warm Reminder

      • 1.For UASP, make sure the device, OS and controller have the UASP function enabled.
      • 2. Always safely remove your disc before unplugging this product.
      • 3. For the 7mm hdd, pls add the additional EVA pad.
      • 4. Win XP 32bit does not support 2TB above.
      • 5. If you would like to change USB cable, pls kindly keep the cable length within 3FT to keep a good performance of the enclosure.

      Package Content

      • 1x USB C SATA Enclosure
      • 1x 1.5ft USB C to USB 3.0 A Cable

          Angel
          3.0 out of 5 stars Almost a good drive enclosure... but excellent customer service!
          Reviewed in the United States on September 8, 2018
          Verified Purchase
          I had high hopes for this drive. The reviews were great. The install of the drive in the enclosure was super easy and the sturdy foam in the enclosure holds the drive well. The issue is with the cable itself. The included cable causes the drive to disconnect when transferring data or even trying to read the drive. I used a USB-C cable I had and it worked perfectly. It’s not the drive. I did connect the same drive with a USB to SATA cable and it had no issues. I’m debating on keeping the enclosure and just purchasing a USB-C cable to use with it but it does suck the included cable does not work as intended.

          UPDATE:

          The company did reach out to me to resolve the issue. I had done my own research and discovered a USB-C cable the company sells with speeds that should match the enclosure and the company did send me the replacement cable for free.           Enjuneer
          5.0 out of 5 stars Good, fair value, legitimate I/O controller that meets SATA III STDs.
          Reviewed in the United States on May 23, 2021
          Verified Purchase
          Just another cheap SATA III interpreter, nothing fancy. It's a middle ground price; these types of modules are very cheap purchased alone (that's the important part of it, anyways). The rest is just injection molded polymer, which is trival in almost every parameter. That's said, I'll give it a 9/10 construction/design rating.

          I haven't tested a 3D NAND SSD yet, I don't have any spares floating around that I can use. I was able to saturate several platter drives, which is a fair test for counterfeit/bogus rip-off I/O controllers, read on for my point and anecdote.

          I just finished returning two different units to Amazon which had the same labeling and screening on the I/O modules as this one, however, the controller was entirely saturated to the point of buffer overflows on a simple raw I/O test, only peaking around 320mbps (BITS, not BYTES). Again, those were cheap clones of this product's I/O controller, which is just ridiculous to me considering the 'scammers' probably saved about 10¢/unit while capping the throughput near USB 2.0 best case. My point is, counterfeit boards are common across a great many platforms of mass produced East Asian sourced parts, some of them are just ripped off reverse engineered and produced at an even lower rate, which is more work than just illegally duplicating an existing design in a number of ways. The difference is, it's the obfuscated counterfeit parts you need be wary of, there's a good chance someone is riding the good reviews and reputation of the legitimate part.

          There's a fair handful of variables that can't really be accounted for by the resale agents, such as your type (make/model/specification) of drive used, and especially user behavior, and that's a BIG one. In many contract jobs, classroom settings with some students, whoever wherever, there's always a couple users that beat the crap out of their storage devices in multiple ways, then claim it's a design fault. Examples, issues with throughput on a packed platter drive with severe fragmentation, not understanding how modes of writing work (sequential, random), having absolutely no clue how various file systems operate, a complete lack of understanding in concept such as performance vs efficiency vs reliability between file systems and their sector type/format/size.

          When I have the time and a spare SATA SSD, I'll run a couple more I/O tests and post results here. I expect this will meet in the high middle range, around 5500mbps. By comparison, and yeah I know it's not an exact analog, I have a NVMe USB-C external that I built, housing a fairly new WD Black NVMe, and I have no issue saturating the I/O very, very close to 10gbps on a 3.1 port or a type-c to type-c interface. So, very generally speaking, I expect around 65-70% of that estimate with this enclosure and a quality SATA III SSD.
          Yes, that's stupid vague, but we aren't talking about a multidisk compound raid array or something remotely mission critical. Also, the tests I ran for this one were entirely sequential; I do not ever intend to run something off of or in accompany with this drive enclosure, I will likely only be using this to move a very large volume of data to one of my non-networked machines, or possibly offload some game ISOs (which I'll be running in RAM anyways, read only from disk).

          On more major benefit to a legitimate, quality I/O like this one, I can comfortably R/W to a fully encrypted volume at speed, and I'm not talking about that BitLocker horse hockey.

          This is a stupid long review for a borderline trivial part... So, I'll close my thoughts on it now.

          Utilizing the throughput of a USB 3.1+ or type-c interface, both separate and compound concurrent I/O, one can expect about a 8.5/10 performance wise, relative to your selection of drive too. A SATA III SSD will hit it's own standard ceiling, which is about 6gbps, and that's really about the absolute best case scenario you're looking at for any external drive with a SATA III interface in the I/O chain (the only way to beat that with SATA III, is by multiple SATA III drives in a logical stripe, more commonly known as raid0. A raid5 arrangement is absolutely acceptable as well)

          3.0 out of 5 stars Very fast indeed, when it works. But unreliable with Gen 2. Choose cable carefully!
          Reviewed in the United Kingdom on November 8, 2018
          Verified Purchase
          I currently have a Crucial M500 1Tb SSD in a Buffalo Thunderbolt enclosure. I get about 320MB/s transfer speeds to my Mac using that setup.

          On USB3 the Buffalo enclosure speed drops slightly, so I was expecting this UGREEN to be similar and certainly not match the Thunderbolt performance.

          However I'm stunned to say that with the SSD installed in this UGREEN enclosure, I was getting 420MB/s sustained speeds on a USB3 (Gen1 ie 5Gbps link) so clearly excellent.

          One down side from my perspective is that the cable supplied is USB-C (enclosure end) to USB-A. I was expecting USB-C at both ends so now have to source another cable. Not the end of the world but does add unexpected cost.

          BUT: when using this with a new Mac mini ie Gen2 USB3.1 (10Gbps) it was terrible. 15MB/s on the USB-C ports and unreliable / disconnects etc. on the USB-A ports. I was going to send it back, but then I bought a decent USB-C to USB-C cable and it absolutely flies with that - getting over 500MB/s sustained speeds.

          I can highly recommend this enclosure if you're looking for something that will perform really well on USB 3.x and you're willing to pay for a decent cable. However it's a bit of a compatibility nightmare with the cable that's included hence only 4 stars which is a shame as this is the fastest enclosure I've ever had, bar none, once you spend hours sorting through the cable problems!

          Simon Tucker
          5.0 out of 5 stars Get maximum speed from your SSD drive at a great price
          Reviewed in the United Kingdom on October 11, 2018
          Verified Purchase
          This was one of the few enclosures I could find that supported:
          1. TRIM - ensures you get maximum life & performance from your SSD
          2. USAP - increases speed over USB 3.0 connections
          3. USB 3.1 Gen 2 - combined with USAP means this enclosure has a faster connection than most SSD drives available today need. It supports speeds up to 10Gbps whilst most SSD drives can only get to around 4-6Gbps, which is 500-750 MB/S - confusing I know as SSDs are all compared on MB/s (Megabyes per second) but USB standards are quoted in is Gbps (Gigabit per second) - TIP: if you want to find our the conversion for your SSD speed just google "mb/s to gbps" and you'll get an online conversion tool.

          I'm getting real world speeds on my Samsung Evo 850 1TB drive connected to an iMac thunderbolt/USB 3.1 port of Sequential write of 456 MB/s and reads of 513 MB/s. The official specs for this drive are 520 MB/s write and 540 MB/s read but from what I understand from reading online reviews is you never get these speeds in real world situations.

          It's great value for the price as I saw some enclosures that were 2x or 3x the price for the same spec. To make sure you get the best performance from the drive make sure you get a good quality USB 3.1 Gen 2 cable that can support the 10 Gbps speed and if you're using a Mac then you will have to get your hands dirty with some simple Terminal commands to turn on TRIM or download one of the TRIM enabler tools available online.

          My only one criticism is the drive comes with a USB C to USB A connector but to hook it up to a fast USB C/thunderbolt port on a Mac you need USB C to USB C cable - would be great if they offered a different version with this cable like some of the competing drives, but it still works out good value if you add in the cost of a £10 USB cable.

          5.0 out of 5 stars Benchmarks and real world usage
          Reviewed in Canada on July 20, 2019
          Verified Purchase
          Some of you may be wondering what speeds this USB 3.1 Gen 2 product can give you. Here are my findings using AS SSD Benchmark 2.0.6821.41776.

          Drive used: Silicone Power A58 512 GB SSD.

          Installed in the computer it got sequential Read / Write speeds of:
          Read: 497.43 MB/s
          Write: 464.02 MB/s

          Using my USB 3.1 GEN 1 type A port (and a generic USB-C to USB-A cable) the Seq read writes were:
          Read: 37.78 MB/s
          Write: 42.25 MB/s

          Using my USB 3.1 GEN 1 type A port and the included UGreen USB-C to USB-A cable the Seq read and writes were:
          Read: 397.61 MB/s
          Write: 414.02 MB/s

          Using my USB 3.1 Gen 2 type C port and dual ended USB-C cable the sequential read and write speeds were:
          Read: 430.29 MB/s
          Write: 463.21 MB/s

          As for real world testing, I copied over 55 files totaling 17GB and results were loosely as follows:
          - USB 3.1 GEN 1 type A port using included UGreen cable, transfer write speed was hovering around 393 MB/s for about 35% of the transfer, then dropped to around 100 MB/s, at times dipping as low as 68 MB/s for the remaining 45 seconds, or 65% of the transfer. I don't know if this is an issue with the drive, enclosure, or Windows 10

          - USB 3.1 GEN 2 type C port using my own type C to type C cable, transfer write speeds were similar to above. Staring off with high 300s and then dropping to 68-100 MB/s after 30% mark.

          I don't usually transfer such large files, but did it for the sake of this review I threw something together.

          So, YMMV.

          My UGreen enclosure looks different than pictured. It's got a clear plastic top, and absolutely no branding anywhere on it. For all intents and purposes, I have no idea who makes this enclosure or the model. I only know it's by UGreen because it came in a UGreen box with a UGreen cable. Then again, my Orico clear plastic enclosure doesn't have any branding on it at all either.
